********************************************************************
* Koronis - Koronis Rift Program
*
* NOTE:  This code assembles to the EXACT same object code found on
*        the original Koronis Rift disk.
*
*        Module size: $5C68  #23656
*        Module CRC : $FA659A (Good)
*        Hdr parity : $1C
*        Exec. off  : $0014  #20
*        Data size  : $6000  #24576
*        Edition    : $30  #48
*        Ty/La At/Rv: $11 $81
*        Prog mod, 6809 Obj, re-ent, R/O
*
* Edt/Rev  YYYY/MM/DD  Modified by
* Comment
* ------------------------------------------------------------------
*          2003/01/12  Boisy G. Pitre
* Disassembled from original binary; patched so that standard output
* is used and /TERM is no longer assumed.
*          2011/08/01  Robert Gault
* Changed two routines that toggle the RS-232 line at $FF20 to the
* single bit sound line at $FF22. This preserves timing and prevents
* DriveWire complications. (The two sound-line gate routines.)

*          2026/07/20  Codex
* Deeply annotated the game systems, recovered semantic code/workspace
* symbols, and verified the result against the current patched binary.
*
* Reverse-engineering overview
* ----------------------------
* Koronis Rift keeps its entire mutable world in one $6000-byte OS-9 data
* area.  KORVAR is loaded over the low part of that area and supplies the
* tables, fonts, object definitions, module records, and initial state used
* by the executable.  The high part contains the 160-byte-wide packed-pixel
* work/display images and the stack.  Most apparently absolute addresses in
* the original disassembly are therefore fields in this per-process area,
* not fixed machine RAM; the symbols below make that ownership explicit.
*
* The top-level controller alternates between the rover view and modal
* scoutcraft/Repo-Tech screens.  Each rover frame advances world and Guardian
* state, projects terrain and movable objects into view space, rasterizes the
* fractal height field into scanline extrema, overlays sprites and cockpit
* instruments, and copies the completed packed-nibble image to the allocated
* OS-9 graphics screen.  Rendering uses the hardware stacks as fast block
* movers/fillers, so several routines deliberately repurpose S or U while
* interrupts are masked or the caller's stack is preserved.
*
* Four parallel entity slots describe the rover and active moving objects.
* Their position, heading, altitude, lifetime, screen coordinates, and model
* indices are stored in small structure-of-arrays tables.  Projection code
* converts world deltas into camera-relative coordinates; collision code
* samples the rift occupancy map and nearby hulk/Guardian positions.  The
* Guardian state machine selects targets, approaches, attacks, retreats, and
* escalates as the rift timer advances.
*
* Salvage is represented by six installed/carried module slots plus an
* eight-entry conveyor ordering.  Each module record carries class, power,
* efficiency, value, and display-art selectors.  Repo-Tech screens decode
* those records, paint icons and numeric fields, install/dismantle modules,
* and update the three-byte kilocredit score.  Weapon and shield values are
* intentionally color dependent: effectiveness is looked up against the
* current Guardian technology rather than treated as a single scalar.
*
* Files are dispatched through one service that opens or creates named OS-9
* files, transfers the requested byte count, and closes the path on every
* exit.  CTITLE.C and CROBOT2.C are run-length decoded into the display;
* KORVAR supplies game assets/state; LEVEL01 through LEVEL20 provide rift
* data; SAVE1 and SAVE2 hold the two-part saved game.  The sound player walks
* compact (duration, pitch) triplets and issues SS.Tone requests, polling the
* joystick so long effects remain interruptible.
*
* The historical CRC in the 2003 header describes the pre-2011 image.  With
* the documented $FF20-to-$FF22 sound-line patch present, this source builds
* to module CRC $EDCFDD.  The annotation and symbol recovery below do not
* change any emitted byte; that patched binary is the comparison baseline.

                                      nam       Koronis
                                      ttl       Koronis Rift Program

                                    IFP1
                                      use       defsfile
                                    ENDC

tylg                                  set       Prgrm+Objct
atrv                                  set       ReEnt+rev
rev                                   set       $01

                                      mod       eom,name,tylg,atrv,start,size

